2 SENATE BILL 413
1 (1) ANY CONSUMER CONTRACT PROVIDED BY A BUSINESS,
2 INCLUDING AN AFFILIATE OR A SUBSIDIARY OF THE BUSINESS, THAT IS DOING
3 BUSINESS UNDER A LICENSE, FRANCHISE AGREEMENT, CERTIFICATE, OR OTHER
4 AUTHORIZATION ISSUED BY A STATE AGENCY, POLITICAL SUBDIVISION, OR PUBLIC
5 UTILITY COMMISSION;
6 (2) A SERVICE REGULATED BY:
7 (I) THE MARYLAND PUBLIC SERVICE COMMISSION;
8 (II) THE FEDERAL COMMUNICATIONS COMMISSION; OR
9 (III) THE FEDERAL ENERGY REGULATORY COMMISSION; OR
10 (3) A PERSON OR BUSINESS LICENSED TO PROVIDE SECURITY
11 SYSTEM SERVICES UNDER TITLE 18 OF THE BUSINESS OCCUPATIONS AND
12 PROFESSIONS ARTICLE.
13 (C) A PROVISION IN A CONSUMER CONTRACT THAT SETS A SHORTER TIME
14 TO BRING AN ACTION UNDER OR ON THE CONSUMER CONTRACT THAN REQUIRED BY
15 THE LAW OF THE STATE WHEN THE CONSUMER CONTRACT IS ISSUED OR DELIVERED
16 IS AGAINST STATE PUBLIC POLICY, ILLEGAL, AND VOID.
17 (C) (D) IF A CONSUMER CONTRACT CONTAINS A PROVISION THAT IS
18 ILLEGAL UNDER THIS SECTION:
19 (1) A COURT MAY NOT GIVE EFFECT TO THE PROVISION; AND
20 (2) A DEFENSE TO LIABILITY UNDER THE CONSUMER CONTRACT MAY
21 NOT BE BASED ON THE SHORTER LIMITATION PERIOD.
22 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall be construed to
23 apply only prospectively and may not be applied or interpreted to have any effect on or
24 application to any contract entered into before the effective date of this Act.
25 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
26 October 1, 2025 June 1, 2026.

